by, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","Kinoulton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Kinoulton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Brooksby, Leicestershire, England":"Brooksby, Leicestershire, England"},"nl":{"estimated 1220–after 1268":"circa 1220–na 1268","1228–1277":"1228–1277","1269–Female":"1269–Overleden","1282–1332":"1282–1332","1250–1324":"1250–1324","1252–1272":"1252–1272","1260–Male":"1260–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1220–1268":"1220–1268","1220":"1220","1252":"1252","1250":"1250","abt 1252":"circa 1252","1272":"1272","abt. 1260":"circa 1260","1260":"1260","1282":"1282","1228":"1228","1259":"1259","1324":"1324","1269":"1269","1224":"1224","1268":"1268","1332":"1332","1277":"1277","estimated 1220":"circa 1220","after 1268":"na 1268","Brooksby, Leics., Eng.":"Brooksby, Leicestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Kinoulton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Kinoulton, Nottinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Brooksby, Leicestershire, England":"Brooksby, Leicestershire, England"},"en":{"estimated 1220–after 1268":"about 1220–after 1268","1228–1277":"1228–1277","1269–Female":"1269–Deceased","1282–1332":"1282–1332","1250–1324":"1250–1324","1252–1272":"1252–1272","1260–Male":"1260–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1220–1268":"1220–1268","1220":"1220","1252":"1252","1250":"1250","abt 1252":"about 1252","1272":"1272","abt. 1260":"about 1260","1260":"1260","1282":"1282","1228":"1228","1259":"1259","1324":"1324","1269":"1269","1224":"1224","1268":"1268","1332":"1332","1277":"1277","estimated 1220":"about 1220","after 1268":"after 1268","Brooksby, Leics., Eng.":"Brooksby, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","Kinoulton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Kinoulton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Brooksby, Leicestershire, England":"Brooksby, Leicestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Villiers","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French and English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Villiers, the name of several places in France, all named from Late Latin <i>villare</i> ‘(part of an) outlying farm, dependent settlement’ (see   Villars  ). Compare   Devilliers  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Villars","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Henri.","French: habitational name from any of various places called Villars, from Late Latin <i>villare</i> ‘(part of an) outlying farm, dependent settlement’, a derivative of Latin <i>villa</i> ‘country house, estate’ (later used of a group of houses forming a settlement)."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":4,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":39,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Richard de Villiers I was born about 1220, in Kinoulton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. He married Maud Hyde after February 1277. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. He died after 1268, in Brooksby, Leicestershire, England."},"et":{"estimated 1220–after 1268":"umbes 1220–pärast 1268","1228–1277":"1228–1277","1269–Female":"1269–Surnud","1282–1332":"1282–1332","1250–1324":"1250–1324","1252–1272":"1252–1272","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1220–1268":"1220–1268","1220":"1220","1252":"1252","1250":"1250","abt 1252":"umbes